@NODE FEATURES "Features"

        @{u}@{fg highlight}                @{uu}

        General features
        @{u}                @{fg text}@{uu}



    -  MUI interface with help bubbles, keyboard support, ...

    -  Localized interface.

    -  Preferences loading, editing, saving with special preferences for each
       output format.

    -  Generation window with ability to pause, continue, abort the generation.
       If you stop the generation, the files already generated remains valid.

    -  Allows to specify a minimum AND maximum age in weeks for output files.

    -  Allows to customise the position of every INDEX field so the program
       can read ANY format of INDEX file (even old and future ones) !

    -  Allows to specify which directories and subdirectories to extract using
       listviews in the prefs window.

    -  Uses TREE file to get description of directories for output files
       and preference window.

    -  Can generate a RECENT type file in the following formats :
       Text, AmigaGuide, HTML and Database !

    -  Can add a search button in AmigaGuide files (needs the SearchGuide tool
       by Gérard Cornu).

    -  Can split the RECENT file (one file for each directory selected) with
       a smart file extension handling. With this feature, even computers with
       low memory can easily use the huge INDEX file :->

    -  Can remove any field form the INDEX (except the file field of course).
       For example, the complete AmigaGuide version of an INDEX takes less
       space than the original INDEX if you remove the dir field !

    -  NO buffer is used for the RECENT file generation (sequential access)
       and the job is done in ONE pass.

    -  When all the selected dirs are scanned, stops reading the INDEX immedia-
       tely :-)

    -  Displays current written file and the current read directory during the
       RECENT file generation.

    -  Displays an accurate progression gauge and a funny busy bar.

    -  It's in EMAILWARE !

@ENDNODE
@NODE REQUIREMENTS "Requirements"

        @{u}@{fg highlight}                                   @{uu}

        Equipment required for POWER Recent
        @{u}                                   @{fg text}@{uu}



    - @{"MUI" LINK MUI } 3.3 or better (Magic User Interface)

    - MCC_Busy class (dev/mui/MCC_Busy_2.3.lha) or with MUI archive.

    - An Amiga with the KickStart 2.04 or better

    - The WIDE version of the Aminet INDEX :

        *   The wide version is in the Aminet /info/index/ directory !
        *   The short version is in the Aminet root directory...
        *   You may use an INDEX from an Aminet CDROM

    - The most recent Aminet TREE file :

        *   You should find it in the root directory
        *   A recent version is present in this archive
        *   This file describes the Aminet directory structure


    - The program was tested on an A1200/68030/28 MHz + 8 MB of Fast + HD

@ENDNODE
@NODE INSTALLATION "Installation"

        @{u}@{fg highlight}            @{uu}

        Installation
        @{u}            @{fg text}@{uu}



    -  Check you've installed MUI correctly

    -  Check you've installed MCC_Busy (MUI custom class) correctly

    -  Move the PW_Recent directory where you want

    -  Click on the POWER_Recent icon

    -  That's all !

@ENDNODE
@NODE USAGE "Usage"

        @{u}@{fg highlight}                  @{uu}

        POWER Recent usage
        @{u}                  @{fg text}@{uu}



        @{" Main window         " LINK "MAIN_WINDOW"       }
        @{" Prefs window        " LINK "PREFS_WINDOW"      }
        @{" Generation window   " LINK "GENERATION_WINDOW" }


        For an efficient usage of the interface you should really have a
look at the @{"MUI" LINK MUI } documentation. Here are some examples :

    -   HELP key     : Shows the on-line help.
    -   Help bubbles : For each gadget an help bubble is available.
    -   TAB key      : Allows you to control the GUI with the keyboard.

@ENDNODE
@NODE MAIN_WINDOW "Main window"

        @{u}@{fg highlight}           @{uu}

        Main window
        @{u}           @{fg text}@{uu}


*  When you launch the program, the main window displays five gadgets :

    -  INDEX file  : Path and name of the source INDEX file from Aminet.
    -  RECENT file : Path and name of the destination file.
    -  The minimum and maximum age sliders allows you to specify the age in
       weeks of the files (lines in the INDEX) you want to extract.
    -  The output format cycle gadget.

    This gadgets initially contain the last saved preferences values but you
can edit them before launching the RECENT file generation, to make some temp-
orary changes without having to : go in the prefs window, make the changes in
the prefs and return to the main window with the `Use' button.

    Each time you come back from the prefs window using `Save' or `Use' button
the new prefs are used for the main window gadgets.


*  The `Run' button launches the RECENT file generation and opens the
   @{"generation window" LINK "GENERATION_WINDOW"}.

*  The `Prefs' button opens the @{"preferences window" LINK "PREFS_WINDOW"}.

*  The `Quit' button terminates the application.

*  The entries in the menu can also be used.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PREFS_WINDOW "Prefs window"

        @{u}@{fg highlight}             @{uu}

        Prefs window
        @{u}             @{fg text}@{uu}



        @{" INDEX   register    " LINK "INDEX"  }
        @{" TREE    register    " LINK "TREE"   }
        @{" RECENT  register    " LINK "RECENT" }


-  `Save' button   : Saves your preferences in the `PROGDIR:PW_Recent.prefs'
                     file and returns to the main window.

-  `Use' button    : Uses the current preferences without saving them and
                     returns to the main window.

-  `Cancel' button : Cancels all changes done to the preferences and returns
                     to the main window.

-  `MUI...' menu item     : Opens the MUI prefs program for this application.

-  `Last saved' menu item : Cancels current prefs and load the last saved prefs.

-  `Default' menu item    : Cancels current prefs and set the default prefs.

@ENDNODE
@NODE GENERATION_WINDOW "Generation window"

        @{u}@{fg highlight}                 @{uu}

        Generation window
        @{u}                 @{fg text}@{uu}




   This window is a new feature of POWER Recent, it allows you to easily control
the generation of your RECENT files. You can see the current read directory,
the current ouput file and a gauge giving you an accurate indication of the
progression of the generation.

   It also displays a busy bar (customisable in the MUI prefs program) to make
the generation time less boring. If you want, you can even iconify the window
during the generation and do anything you want (thanks for the multitasking).

*  The `Continue' button allows you to continue the generation after a pause.

*  The `Pause' button allows you to pause the generation. You can even inspect
   the already generated files (in split mode).

*  The `Abort' button terminates the generation. You can still use the already
   generated files.

@ENDNODE
@NODE INDEX "INDEX register"

        @{u}@{fg highlight}              @{uu}

        INDEX register
        @{u}              @{fg text}@{uu}



-  INDEX file : Path and name of the source INDEX file from Aminet.

-  The sliders allows you to specify the exact position of each field in the
   INDEX file (start column and end column).

-  The checkboxes allows you to select which field you want to keep in your
   RECENT files.

      *  The INDEX format changes from time to time. In this case, you only
         have to correctly set the sliders to the new positions.

      *  Setting the sliders to incorrect values can lead to strange effects
         in the output RECENT file (not too nasty).

      *  If you have a wide version of the INDEX and want to output a short
         format file, you only have to set the end column of the description
         field to the wanted width (80 for example).
@ENDNODE
@NODE TREE "TREE register"

        @{u}@{fg highlight}             @{uu}

        TREE register
        @{u}             @{fg text}@{uu}


-  TREE file : Path and name of the source TREE file from Aminet.

-  Once you have selected the good TREE file you should press the `Load' or
   `Update' button to be able to select the directories and subdirectories
   you want to extract from the INDEX file.

      *  The `Load' button will clear the two listviews, load the specified
         TREE file and select all the directories and subdirectories.

      *  The `Update' button replaces the contents of the listviews with the
         specified TREE file but remember the state of the old directories and
         subdirectories. The really new directories and subdirectories are
         set in the selected state.

      *  The `All' button select all the directories and subdirectories.

      *  The `None' button unselect all the directories and subdirectories.

      *  The TREE file is only accessed by the preferences ( `Load' and
         `Update' buttons), not during the RECENT file generation.

-  The two listviews allows you to browse into the Aminet dirs structure and
   to select/unselect the directories or subdirectories you want to extract
   from your INDEX file. The left listview contain all the Aminet dirs, the
   right one contain the subdirs of the current dir.

-  The text gadget below the listviews shows the description of the selected
   dir or subdir.

-  The checkbox gadget below the listviews shows the state of the selected
   dir or subdir.

      *  If you unselect a directory, this directory won't be extracted
         whatever is the state of the subdirs of this dir.

      *  When you have selected a subdir of one dir and you want to change the
         state of this dir (not the subdir) you can double click on the dir
         in the left listview.
@ENDNODE
@NODE RECENT "RECENT register"

        @{u}@{fg highlight}               @{uu}

        RECENT register
        @{u}               @{fg text}@{uu}


-  RECENT file : Path and name of the destination file (the one which will be
   generated from the source INDEX file.

-  The minimum and maximum age sliders allows you to specify the age in weeks
   of the files (lines in the INDEX) you want to extract.

-  Output format : specify the RECENT file format.

-  Split RECENT file : allows you to subdivide the RECENT file in subfiles
   (one for each selected dir).

      *  The subfiles will be created in the same directory as the RECENT file.

      *  The name of the subfiles will be :

            `RECENT base' + `_' + `dir name' + `optional RECENT extension'

         The supported extensions are :

            `.doc' and `.txt' for Text format
            `.guide' for AmigaGuide format
            `.html' for HTML format
            `.data' for Database format

         ex : if the name of your RECENT file is `RAM:RECENT.guide' and the
              output format is AmigaGuide then the subfiles will be :

                    RAM:RECENT_biz.guide
                    RAM:RECENT_dev.guide
                    ...

      *  The Output Dirs Header allows you to output a description of each
         subdirectory before outputting the files. It's very useful if you
         want to remove the dir field from the INDEX.

      *  For the AmigaGuide format, you can add a search button to your files.
         This button will call the SearchGuide program (© 1994-96 by Gérard Cornu).
         The archives can be downloaded from Aminet (text/hyper directory).

      *  Even if the split option if specified, the main RECENT file is gene-
         rated (except for the Database format).

         In Text format it contains the list of subfiles and their description.

         In AmigaGuide and HTML format it contains links to main dirs and their
         subdirs. When you click on a subdir link it opens the corresponding dir
         subfile.

         Note that the subfiles are also in AmigaGuide format and contains
         a menu to access to the subdirs of the subfile dir.

         To access to subfiles, the main RECENT file uses relative paths so
         you can generate the files in the RAM and then copy them anywhere.

         However the subfiles must always be in the same dir as the main RECENT
         file in order to use the subfiles auto loading feature.

         But if you don't need the main RECENT file, the subfiles are totally
         independent AmigaGuide files.

         I hope it's clear for everyone !  :-))

      *  The Database format output a first line with the description of the
         field separated with TABs and then the files separated by a line feed.

@ENDNODE
